gskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0442\u044e\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Klimlevo''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043b\u0438\u043c\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Shemogodskoye Rural Settlement, [[Velikoustyugsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 10 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Veliky Ustyug]] is 29 km, to Aristovo is 13 km. Sondas is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klimlevo"}
{"title_page": "Shubhalisho\u02bf", "text_new": "'''Shubhalisho\u02bf''' ({{lang-ar|Shuw\u1e25\u0101l\u012bsh\u014d\u02bf}}{{sfn|Blois|2004|p=599}}){{efn|Also spelled '''Shubhhal-Isho''' or '''Shub\u1e25a-l\u012bsh\u014d\u02bf''', meaning \"praise to Jesus\".{{sfn|Brock|2015|p=560}}}} was an [[Church of the East|East Syriac]] monk, missionary and martyr of the late 8th century.{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=516, gives c. 790}}\n\nAccording to [[Thomas of Marg\u0101]]'s ''Book of Governors'', Shubhalisho\u02bf was an [[Ishmaelites|Ishmaelite]] (i.e., an [[Arab]]) and his native language was [[Arabic]]. He was probably an [[\u02bfIb\u0101d\u012b]], a native Christian of [[\u1e24irt\u0101]], since he was \"trained in the Holy Scriptures and instructed\" in [[Arabic literature]].{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} He was also fluent in [[Syriac language|Syriac]] and [[Persian language|Persian]].{{sfn|Mingana|1925|pp=307\u2013308}} He became a monk at the [[monastery of Beth \u02bfAbe]].{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=166}} There he suffered abuse at the hands of his fellow monks until the Patriarch [[Timothy I (Nestorian patriarch)|Timothy I]] rebuked them.{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}}\n\nShortly after 780, Shubhalisho\u02bf was commissioned by the patriarch to lead a team of monks to evangelise the regions of [[Daylam]] and [[Gilan]]. For this purpose, Timothy consecrated him [[metropolitan bishop]] of [[Dioceses of the Church of the East to 1318#Dailam, Gilan and Muqan|Daylam and Gilan]].{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=166}} According to Thomas, he went \"with exceedingly great splendour, for barbarian nations need to see a little worldly pomp and show to attract them ... to Christianity\".{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} This was paid for by wealthy local Syriac Christians.{{sfn|Wood|2019|p=149 n58}} The Daylamites were predominantly [[Zoroastrians]] and [[Ancient Iranian religion|pagans]],{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=166}} although Thomas describes Shubhalisho\u02bf as also preaching to [[Marcionites]] and [[Manichaeans]].{{sfn|Blois|2004|p=599}} His preaching was accompanied by miracles, since, according to Thomas, \"the Divine dispensation is accustomed to shew forth mighty works at the beginning of Divine operations.\"{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} Thomas says that \"he taught and baptised many towns and numerous villages\", built churches, established ministers, ordered the teaching of the [[Psalms]] and hymns and went \"deep inland to the farthest end of the East.\"{{sfn|Mingana|1925|pp=307\u2013308}}\n\nShubhalisho\u02bf remained for many years in Daylam and Gilan. He was assassinated by some disgruntled Zoroastrians after returning to his monastery. A monk, Qardagh, from within the mission was appointed to succeed him as metropolitan and the mission continued.{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=166}}{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} Shubhalisho\u02bf's life is known through several distinct passages in the ''Book of Governors'', which Thomas wrote around 840. Thomas is full of praise for Shubhalisho\u02bf's education and abilities and gives him the title [[Mar|Rabban Mar]]. He names as one of his sources \"the letter which some merchants and secretaries of the kings, who had penetrated as far as [those countries of the Dailamites and Gilanians] for the sake of commerce and of affairs of State, wrote to Mar Timothy.\"{{sfn|Mingana|1925|pp=307\u2013308}} He also names the Patriarch [[Abraham II (Nestorian patriarch)|Abraham II]] as one of his sources.{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} Shubhalisho\u02bf is also mentioned in Letter 47 of Timothy I, written shortly before the patriarch's death in 828. Timothy calls him Shubhalisho\u02bf of Beth Daylamaye and says that he \"plaited a crown of martyrdom.\"{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|p=69}}{{sfn|Brock|1997|pp=245\u2013250}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{EI2|volume=12|title=Mar\u1e33iy\u016bniyya|first=F. C. de|last=Blois|pages=599\u2013600}}\n*{{cite book |first=Sebastian |last=Brock |authorlink=Sebastian P. Brock |year=1997 |title=A Brief Outline of Syriac Literature |location=Kottyam |publisher=St Ephrem's Ecumenical Research Institute |url=https://archive.org/details/ABriefOutlineOfSyriacLiterature_267/page/n1/mode/2up}}\n*{{cite book |first=Sebastian |last=Brock |title=Jesus in History, Legend, Scripture, and Tradition: A World Encyclopedia |volume=Vol. 2 |editor1=Leslie Houlden |editor2=Antone Minard |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2015 |chapter=Syriac Tradition |pages=556\u2013560}}\n*{{cite thesis |last=Cochrane |first=Steve |year=2014 |title=From Beit Abhe to Angamali: Connections, Functions and Roles of the Church of the East's Monasteries in Ninth-Century Christian\u2013Muslim Relations |type=PhD diss. |institution=Middlesex University |url=http://eprints.mdx.ac.uk/13988/1/SCochrane_thesis.pdf}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Mingana |first=Alphonse |authorlink=Alphonse Mingana |title=The Early Spread of Christianity in Central Asia and the Far East: A New Document |journal=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library |volume=9 |issue=2 |year=1925 |pages=297\u2013371 |url=https://www.escholar.manchester.ac.uk/api/datastream?publicationPid=uk-ac-man-scw:1m1173&datastreamId=POST-PEER-REVIEW-PUBLISHERS-DOCUMENT.PDF}}\n*{{cite book |first=David |last=Wilmshurst |title=The Martyred Church: A History of the Church of the East |publisher=East and West Publishing |year=2011}}\n*{{cite book |last=Wood |first=Philip |chapter=Changing Geographies: West Syrian Ecclesiastical Historiography, AD 700\u2013850 |pages=136\u2013163 |title=Historiography and Space in Late Antiquity |editor=Peter Van Nuffelen |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2019}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:8th-century births]]\n[[Category:8th-century Christian martyrs]]\n[[Category:Arab Christians]]\n[[Category:8th-century people of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Nestorians in the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Syrian Christian monks]]\n[[Category:Christian missionaries in Iran]]\n[[Category:History of Gilan]]\n", "text_old": "'''Shubhalisho\u02bf''' ({{lang-ar|Shuw\u1e25\u0101l\u012bsh\u014d\u02bf}}){{efn|Also spelled '''Shubhhal-Isho''' or '''Shub\u1e25a-l\u012bsh\u014d\u02bf''', meaning \"praise to Jesus\".{{sfn|Brock|2015|p=560}}}} was an [[Church of the East|East Syriac]] monk, missionary and martyr of the late 8th century.{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=516, gives c. 790}}\n\nAccording to [[Thomas of Marg\u0101]]'s ''Book of Governors'', Shubhalisho\u02bf was an [[Ishmaelites|Ishmaelite]] (i.e., an [[Arab]]) and his native language was [[Arabic]]. He was probably an [[\u02bfIb\u0101d\u012b]], a native Christian of [[\u1e24irt\u0101]], since he was \"trained in the Holy Scriptures and instructed\" in [[Arabic literature]].{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} He was also fluent in [[Syriac language|Syriac]] and [[Persian language|Persian]].{{sfn|Mingana|1925|pp=307\u2013308}} He became a monk at the [[monastery of Beth \u02bfAbe]].{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=166}} There he suffered abuse at the hands of his fellow monks until the Patriarch [[Timothy I (Nestorian patriarch)|Timothy I]] rebuked them.{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}}\n\nShortly after 780, Shubhalisho\u02bf was commissioned by the patriarch to lead a team of monks to evangelise the regions of [[Daylam]] and [[Gilan]]. For this purpose, Timothy consecrated him [[metropolitan bishop]] of [[Dioceses of the Church of the East to 1318#Dailam, Gilan and Muqan|Daylam and Gilan]].{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=166}} According to Thomas, he went \"with exceedingly great splendour, for barbarian nations need to see a little worldly pomp and show to attract them ... to Christianity\".{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} This was paid for by wealthy local Syriac Christians.{{sfn|Wood|2019|p=149 n58}} The Daylamites were predominantly [[Zoroastrians]] and [[Ancient Iranian religion|pagans]],{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=166}} although Thomas describes Shubhalisho\u02bf as also preaching to [[Marcionites]] and [[Manichaeans]].{{sfn|Blois|2004|p=599}} His preaching was accompanied by miracles, since, according to Thomas, \"the Divine dispensation is accustomed to shew forth mighty works at the beginning of Divine operations.\"{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} Thomas says that \"he taught and baptised many towns and numerous villages\", built churches, established ministers, ordered the teaching of the [[Psalms]] and hymns and went \"deep inland to the farthest end of the East.\"{{sfn|Mingana|1925|pp=307\u2013308}}\n\nShubhalisho\u02bf remained for many years in Daylam and Gilan. He was assassinated by some disgruntled Zoroastrians after returning to his monastery. A monk, Qardagh, from within the mission was appointed to succeed him as metropolitan and the mission continued.{{sfn|Wilmshurst|2011|p=166}}{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} Shubhalisho\u02bf's life is known through several distinct passages in the ''Book of Governors'', which Thomas wrote around 840. Thomas is full of praise for Shubhalisho\u02bf's education and abilities and gives him the title [[Mar|Rabban Mar]]. He names as one of his sources \"the letter which some merchants and secretaries of the kings, who had penetrated as far as [those countries of the Dailamites and Gilanians] for the sake of commerce and of affairs of State, wrote to Mar Timothy.\"{{sfn|Mingana|1925|pp=307\u2013308}} He also names the Patriarch [[Abraham II (Nestorian patriarch)|Abraham II]] as one of his sources.{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|pp=59\u201362}} Shubhalisho\u02bf is also mentioned in Letter 47 of Timothy I, written shortly before the patriarch's death in 828. Timothy calls him Shubhalisho\u02bf of Beth Daylamaye and says that he \"plaited a crown of martyrdom.\"{{sfn|Cochrane|2014|p=69}}{{sfn|Brock|1997|pp=245\u2013250}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin|30em}}\n*{{EI2|volume=12|title=Mar\u1e33iy\u016bniyya|first=F. C. de|last=Blois|pages=599\u2013600}}\n*{{cite book |first=Sebastian |last=Brock |authorlink=Sebastian P. Brock |year=1997 |title=A Brief Outline of Syriac Literature |location=Kottyam |publisher=St Ephrem's Ecumenical Research Institute |url=https://archive.org/details/ABriefOutlineOfSyriacLiterature_267/page/n1/mode/2up}}\n*{{cite book |first=Sebastian |last=Brock |title=Jesus in History, Legend, Scripture, and Tradition: A World Encyclopedia |volume=Vol. 2 |editor1=Leslie Houlden |editor2=Antone Minard |publisher=ABC-CLIO |year=2015 |chapter=Syriac Tradition |pages=556\u2013560}}\n*{{cite thesis |last=Cochrane |first=Steve |year=2014 |title=From Beit Abhe to Angamali: Connections, Functions and Roles of the Church of the East's Monasteries in Ninth-Century Christian\u2013Muslim Relations |type=PhD diss. |institution=Middlesex University |url=http://eprints.mdx.ac.uk/13988/1/SCochrane_thesis.pdf}}\n*{{cite journal |last=Mingana |first=Alphonse |authorlink=Alphonse Mingana |title=The Early Spread of Christianity in Central Asia and the Far East: A New Document |journal=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library |volume=9 |issue=2 |year=1925 |pages=297\u2013371 |url=https://www.escholar.manchester.ac.uk/api/datastream?publicationPid=uk-ac-man-scw:1m1173&datastreamId=POST-PEER-REVIEW-PUBLISHERS-DOCUMENT.PDF}}\n*{{cite book |first=David |last=Wilmshurst |title=The Martyred Church: A History of the Church of the East |publisher=East and West Publishing |year=2011}}\n*{{cite book |last=Wood |first=Philip |chapter=Changing Geographies: West Syrian Ecclesiastical Historiography, AD 700\u2013850 |pages=136\u2013163 |title=Historiography and Space in Late Antiquity |editor=Peter Van Nuffelen |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2019}}\n{{refend}}\n\n[[Category:8th-century births]]\n[[Category:8th-century Christian martyrs]]\n[[Category:Arab Christians]]\n[[Category:8th-century people of the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Nestorians in the Abbasid Caliphate]]\n[[Category:Syrian Christia