{"title_page": "Klepikovo, Velikoustyugsky District, Vologda Oblast", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Klepikovo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041a\u043b\u0435\u043f\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Velikoustyugsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|60|56|N|46|26|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/velikoustyugskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0442\u044e\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Klepikovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043b\u0435\u043f\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Krasavinskoye Rural Settlement, [[Velikoustyugsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 29 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Veliky Ustyug]] is 21 km, to Vasilyevskoye is 1 km. Vasilyevskoye is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Klepikovo\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041a\u043b\u0435\u043f\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Velikoustyugsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|60|56|N|46|26|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/velikoustyugskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0442\u044e\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Klepikovo''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u043b\u0435\u043f\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0432\u043e}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Krasavinskoye Rural Settlement, [[Velikoustyugsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 29 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Veliky Ustyug]] is 21 km, to Vasilyevskoye is 1 km. Vasilyevskoye is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klepikovo,_Velikoustyugsky_District,_Vologda_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "Kichuga", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Kichuga\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041a\u0438\u0447\u0443\u0433\u0430\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Settlement\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Velikoustyugsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|60|37|N|45|40|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/velikoustyugskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0442\u044e\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Kichuga''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0438\u0447\u0443\u0433\u0430}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|settlement]]) in Opokskoye Rural Settlement, [[Velikoustyugsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 35 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Veliky Ustyug]] is 47.5 km, to Verkhneye Anisimovo is 7 km. Chermyanino is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Kichuga\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u041a\u0438\u0447\u0443\u0433\u0430\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Settlement\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Velikoustyugsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|60|37|N|45|40|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/velikoustyugskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0412\u0435\u043b\u0438\u043a\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0442\u044e\u0433\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Kichuga''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0438\u0447\u0443\u0433\u0430}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|settlement]]) in Opokskoye Rural Settlement, [[Velikoustyugsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 35 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Veliky Ustyug]] is 47.5 km, to Verkhneye Anisimovo is 7 km. Chermyanino is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Velikoustyugsky District]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kichuga"}
{"title_page": "Hollywood Palladium", "text_new": "{{Infobox venue\n| name              = Hollywood Palladium\n| image             = Hollywood Palladium 2012.jpg\n| image_size        = 250\n| image_caption     = The Hollywood Palladium in June 2012 (post-2008 renovation)\n| nickname          = The Palladium\n| pushpin_map       = Los Angeles#California#USA\n| pushpin_map_caption   = \n| location          = 6215 [[Sunset Boulevard]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| coordinates       = {{Coord|34.098007|-118.32421|display=inline,title}}\n| type              = [[List of concert halls|Concert Hall]]\n| genre             = [[Big Band]], [[Rock and Roll]], [[Pop Music]]\n| broke_ground      = June 10, 1940\n| built             = 1940\n| opened            = {{Start date|1940|10|31}}\n| renovated         = 2007\u20132008\n| expanded          = \n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner             = Palladium Investors Ltd.\n| operator          = [[Live Nation (events promoter)|Live Nation]]\n| former_names      = \n| seating_type      = Standing room only, dance floor\n| seating_capacity  = 3800\n| publictransit={{LACMTA link logo}}{{LACMTA icon strip|Red}} [[Hollywood/Vine (Los Angeles Metro station)|Hollywood/Vine]]\n| website           = [http://www.livenation.com/venues/14586/hollywood-palladium livenation.com]\n}}\n[[File:Hollywood Palladium.jpg|thumb|The Palladium in 2005, prior to 2008 renovation]]\n[[File:Hollywood Palladium in 1947.jpg|thumb|right|Bandleader [[Opie Cates]] was on the bill in 1947.]]\nThe '''Hollywood Palladium''' is a [[theater (building)|theater]] located at 6215 [[Sunset Boulevard]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]]. It was built in a [[Streamline Moderne]],<ref name=\"Rasmussen\"/> [[Art Deco]] style and includes an 11,200 square foot (1040&nbsp;m\u00b2) dance floor including a mezzanine and a floor level with room for up to 3,800 people.  The theater was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2016.\n\n==History==\n''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' publisher [[Norman Chandler]] funded the construction of the [[art deco]] Hollywood Palladium at a cost of $1.6 million in 1940.<ref name=\"Jezek\" /> It was built where the original [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] lot once stood<ref name=\"Light\">Scott T. Sterling, Light it Up! The Rad Return of a Hollywood Gem, October 15, 2008, Metromix Los Angeles</ref> by film producer [[Maury Cohen|Maurice Cohen]] and is located between Argyle and El Centro avenues. The dance hall was designed by [[Gordon Kaufmann]], architect of the [[Greystone Mansion]], the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' building and the [[Santa Anita Racetrack]] in [[Arcadia]].<ref name=\"Rasmussen\">{{Cite news | last1 = Rasmussen | first1 = Cecelia |title = Palladium keeps in swing of things | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = October 7, 2007 | page= B2 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2007/oct/07/local/me-then7 | accessdate = February 6, 2016}}</ref> He was also the architect for the [[Hoover Dam]] and early [[Caltech]] dorms.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\nThe ballroom opened on October 31, 1940<ref name=\"Jezek\"/> with a dance featuring [[Tommy Dorsey|Tommy Dorsey and his Orchestra]] and band vocalist [[Frank Sinatra]].<ref name=\"Light\"/> It had six bars serving liquor and two more serving soft drinks and a $1 cover charge and a $3 charge for dinner.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\nDuring World War II, the Palladium hosted radio broadcasts featuring [[Betty Grable]] greeting servicemens' song requests. Big Band acts began losing popularity in the 1950s, causing the Palladium to hold charity balls, political events, auto shows, and rock concerts. In 1961, it became the home of the long-running ''[[The Lawrence Welk Show|Lawrence Welk Show]]''.<ref name=\"Jezek\">{{cite book |title=Hollywood: Now & Then|last1=Jezek |first1=George Ross |last2=Wanamaker |first2=Marc |year=2002 |publisher=George Ross Jezek Photography & Publishing |location=San Diego, CA |isbn=0-9701036-1-1 |oclc= |pages=92\u201393 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |title=The Hollywood Palladium|url=http://wikimapia.org/306199/Hollywood-Palladium |work= |publisher=Wikimapia.org |date= |accessdate=September 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1955-1976, the venue was the scene of Latin Music Orchestras for ragers sponsored by radio personality [[Chico Sesma]] titled ''Latin Holidays,\u201d featuring childhood friend  [[Ray Vasquez]] Recording Artist, Lead Vocalist and Trombonist. The Tito Puente Orchestra performed regularly between 1957-1977 to sold-out houses of 5000.<ref>Josephine Powell, \"Tito Puente: When The Drums Are Dreaming\", Author House 2007.</ref>\n\nPresident [[John F. Kennedy]] attended a dinner given in his honor by the California Democratic Party at the Palladium on November 18, 1961.\n\nIn 1964, it was announced that none of the jazz bands scheduled were to be paid and a riot ensued after the show was cancelled.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\nThe Joe Loco Orchestra and show performed on the March 1965 Latin Holiday with singer/dancer Josephine \"Josie\" Powell.\n\nPop Expo '69, referred to as a \"teenage fair,\" was a youth-oriented event held from 28 March to 6 April 1969 at the Palladium, and included performances by [[The Jimi Hendrix Experience]] and the [[MC5]].\n\nIn 1973 Stevie Wonder performed with [[Taj Mahal (musician)|Taj Mahal]] in what was advertised as an \"Afrocentric concert\" to benefit African refugees.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\nBeginning in the 1980s and 90s, punk rock, [[Rap music|rap]] and [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] concerts started to be booked at the venue. Several white power disturbances resulted, eventually leading to the Palladium closing for eight weeks, starting in February 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1994-12-14-ca-8811-story.html |title=Story |date=December 14, 1994 |website= www.latimes.com|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nSince 1985, the theater has been owned by Palladium Investors Ltd., a privately held group. Curfews were implemented in 1993 and a show by [[Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch]] was called off because of a brawl that occurred a few nights earlier, .<ref name=\"Light\"/> It was also used for Hollywood celebrity parties.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\n==Renovation and reopening==\nIn 2007, the owners agreed to a long-term lease to operate, manage and exclusively book the Hollywood Palladium with [[Live Nation]], a [[Los Angeles]]-based company.<ref name=\"billboardOct2008\"/>\n\nThe Palladium reopened with a Jay-Z concert on October 15, 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filter-mag.com/index.php?id=14264&c=1 |title=Filter-Mag.com |publisher=Filter-mag.com |date= |accessdate=2008-11-29}}</ref> after a year-long, multimillion-dollar renovation by Live Nation. The renovation included an overhaul of the venue's interior and exterior, a new dance floor, expanded concessions, upgraded restrooms and improvements to the stage infrastructure. Jay-Z performed for nearly an hour-and-half, backed by an eight-piece band and [[DJ AM]], who played his first show after surviving a plane crash in South Carolina.<ref name=\"billboardOct2008\">{{Cite news|last=Peters |first=Mitchell |title=Jay-Z Christens New Hollywood Palladium |newspaper=Billboard Magazine |date=October 16, 2008 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043761/jay-z-christens-new-hollywood-palladium |format=&ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=author%3APeters+intitle%3AJay-Z+Christens+New+Hollywood+Palladium&as_publication=&as_ylo=2008&as_yhi=2008&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> |postscript= |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131119080215/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043761/jay-z-christens-new-hollywood-palladium |archivedate=November 19, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The Hollywood Palladium was also used as the memorial service site for [[DJ AM]] on September 3, 2009.<ref>{{cite news | author=Adam Bryant | title=DJ AM Funeral and Burial to Be Held Wednesday | url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/DJ-AM-Funeral-1009412.aspx | work=TVGuide.com | date=2 September 2009 | accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2008-2009 season, a yearlong table for four cost $30,000.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\n===Residential expansion===\nAn expansion of the Palladium property parking lot was approved by the Los Angeles City council on March 2016. The plan consists of two 28 story residential towers that surrounds the historic music venue. Each tower will stand 350 feet tall and create 731 condominiums, 24,000 sq ft store front retail space and a below grade parking garage. The Towers were designed by [[Stanley Saitowits]] of [[Natoma Architects]] for developer Crescent Heights. The \"L\" shaped design resembles and echoes the [[Streamline Moderne]] - art deco design of the Palladium.\n\nThe local [[AIDS Healthcare Foundation]] (AHF) filed a lawsuit in 2016 citing over development and improper approval process. One of many local lawsuits filed by AHF president Michael Weinstein.<ref>{{cite web|author=July 13, 2018, 10:00AMSteven Sharp Comments |url=https://urbanize.la/post/hollywoods-palladium-development-score-legal-victory |title=Hollywood's Palladium Development Score a Legal Victory |publisher=Urbanize LA |date=2018-07-13 |accessdate=2020-01-20}}</ref> In August 2018, the district court ruled all steps were taken during [[California Environmental Quality Act|EIR/DEIR]]. The AHF filed a appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://urbanize.la/post/la-city-council-approves-palladium-residences|title=L.A. City Council Approves Palladium Residences|date=23 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref> The AHF lost the appeal in November 2019 and Crescent Heights plans to proceed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://urbanize.la/tags/hollywood-palladium |title=Hollywood Palladium News |publisher=Urbanize.la |date= |accessdate=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Hollywood Palladium has been featured in many movies and TV shows over the years:\n*''[[The Day of the Locust]]'' (1975).<ref>Lawson, Kristan, & Rufus, Anneli (2000). ''California Babylon'', p. 35.  New York:  St. Martin's Press.</ref>\n*''[[Skatetown, U.S.A.]]'' (1979).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0079912/|title=Skatetown, U.S.A.|date=1 October 1979|publisher=|accessdate=27 June 2018|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/57090|title=AFI-Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n*The final concert scene in ''[[The Blues Brothers (film)|The Blues Brothers]]'' depicted as \"Palace Hotel Ballroom\". The exterior was actually the [[South Shore Cultural Center|South Shore Country Club]] in [[Chicago]]. (1980).<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n*[[Richard Pryor]] performed two dates in December 1981 and was filmed for the theatrical release ''[[Richard Pryor: Live on the Sunset Strip]]'' in March 1982.      \n*[[Keith Richards]] released a CD and DVD of his solo concert ''[[Live at the Hollywood Palladium, December 15, 1988]]''.\n* The [[punk rock|punk]] band [[Bad Religion]] recorded ''[[Live at the Palladium (Bad Religion DVD)|Live at the Palladium]]'' in 2006, a collection from their two days of performances.\n* [[Thrash Metal]] band [[Megadeth]] filmed a live DVD based on the 20th anniversary of their album ''[[Rust in Peace]]'' at The Palladium.\n* [[Luna Sea]] performed their first American concert at the Palladium on December 4, 2010. It was recorded in [[3D film|3D]] and released as both a live album and [[concert film]], ''[[Luna Sea 3D in Los Angeles]]''.<ref name=\"Luna Sea\">{{cite web| title= LUNA SEA announces the release date for their 3D live movie| work=Tokyo Hive| date= 2011-04-30| url=http://www.tokyohive.com/2011/04/luna-sea-announces-the-release-date-for-their-3d-live-movie/| accessdate = 2011-06-11}}</ref>\n*In 2016 [[Dave Chappelle]] filmed his [[Netflix]] special at the Palladium.\n* The exterior appears in the final episode of ''[[Adam-12]]''.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Architecture|Greater Los Angeles|National Register of Historic Places|Theatre}}\n*[[List of music venues in Los Angeles]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Los Angeles]]\n*[[Theater in California]]\n*[[House Of Blues]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Grammy Award venues}}\n{{Live Nation}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in California}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Hollywood]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Concert halls in California]]\n[[Category:Hollywood history and culture]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sunset Boulevard (Los Angeles)]]\n[[Category:1940 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Streamline Moderne architecture in California]]\n[[Category:Theatres on the National Register of Historic Places in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award venues]]\n[[Category:Theatres completed in 1940]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox venue\n| name              = Hollywood Palladium\n| image             = Hollywood Palladium 2012.jpg\n| image_size        = 250\n| image_caption     = The Hollywood Palladium in June 2012 (post-2008 renovation)\n| nickname          = The Palladium\n| pushpin_map       = Los Angeles#California#USA\n| pushpin_map_caption   = \n| location          = 6215 [[Sunset Boulevard]], [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]\n| coordinates       = {{Coord|34.098007|-118.32421|display=inline,title}}\n| type              = [[List of concert halls|Concert Hall]]\n| genre             = [[Big Band]], [[Rock and Roll]], [[Pop Music]]\n| broke_ground      = June 10, 1940\n| built             = 1940\n| opened            = {{Start date|1940|10|31}}\n| renovated         = 2007\u20132008\n| expanded          = \n| closed            = \n| demolished        = \n| owner             = Palladium Investors Ltd.\n| operator          = [[Live Nation (events promoter)|Live Nation]]\n| former_names      = \n| seating_type      = Standing room only, dance floor\n| seating_capacity  = 3800\n| publictransit={{LACMTA link logo}}{{LACMTA icon strip|Red}} [[Hollywood/Vine (Los Angeles Metro station)|Hollywood/Vine]]\n| website           = [http://www.livenation.com/venues/14586/hollywood-palladium livenation.com]\n}}\n[[File:Hollywood Palladium.jpg|thumb|The Palladium in 2005, prior to 2008 renovation]]\n[[File:Hollywood Palladium in 1947.jpg|thumb|right|Bandleader [[Opie Cates]] was on the bill in 1947.]]\nThe '''Hollywood Palladium''' is a [[theater (building)|theater]] located at 6215 [[Sunset Boulevard]] in [[Hollywood]], [[California]]. It was built in a [[Streamline Moderne]],<ref name=\"Rasmussen\"/> [[Art Deco]] style and includes an 11,200 square foot (1040&nbsp;m\u00b2) dance floor including a mezzanine and a floor level with room for up to 3,800 people.  The theater was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2016.\n\n==History==\n''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' publisher [[Norman Chandler]] funded the construction of the [[art deco]] Hollywood Palladium at a cost of $1.6 million in 1940.<ref name=\"Jezek\" /> It was built where the original [[Paramount Pictures|Paramount]] lot once stood<ref name=\"Light\">Scott T. Sterling, Light it Up! The Rad Return of a Hollywood Gem, October 15, 2008, Metromix Los Angeles</ref> by film producer [[Maury Cohen|Maurice Cohen]] and is located between Argyle and El Centro avenues. The dance hall was designed by [[Gordon Kaufmann]], architect of the [[Greystone Mansion]], the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' building and the [[Santa Anita Racetrack]] in [[Arcadia]].<ref name=\"Rasmussen\">{{Cite news | last1 = Rasmussen | first1 = Cecelia |title = Palladium keeps in swing of things | newspaper = [[Los Angeles Times]] | date = October 7, 2007 | page= B2 | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2007/oct/07/local/me-then7 | accessdate = February 6, 2016}}</ref> He was also the architect for the [[Hoover Dam]] and early [[Caltech]] dorms.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\nThe ballroom opened on October 31, 1940<ref name=\"Jezek\"/> with a dance featuring [[Tommy Dorsey|Tommy Dorsey and his Orchestra]] and band vocalist [[Frank Sinatra]].<ref name=\"Light\"/> It had six bars serving liquor and two more serving soft drinks and a $1 cover charge and a $3 charge for dinner.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\nDuring World War II, the Palladium hosted radio broadcasts featuring [[Betty Grable]] greeting servicemens' song requests. Big Band acts began losing popularity in the 1950s, causing the Palladium to hold charity balls, political events, auto shows, and rock concerts. In 1961, it became the home of the long-running ''[[The Lawrence Welk Show|Lawrence Welk Show]]''.<ref name=\"Jezek\">{{cite book |title=Hollywood: Now & Then|last1=Jezek |first1=George Ross |last2=Wanamaker |first2=Marc |year=2002 |publisher=George Ross Jezek Photography & Publishing |location=San Diego, CA |isbn=0-9701036-1-1 |oclc= |pages=92\u201393 |url= |accessdate=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= |title=The Hollywood Palladium|url=http://wikimapia.org/306199/Hollywood-Palladium |work= |publisher=Wikimapia.org |date= |accessdate=September 27, 2009}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1955-1976, the venue was the scene of Latin Music Orchestras for ragers sponsored by radio personality [[Chico Sesma]] titled ''Latin Holidays,\u201d featuring childhood friend  [[Ray Vasquez]] Recording Artist, Lead Vocalist and Trombonist. The Tito Puente Orchestra performed regularly between 1957-1977 to sold-out houses of 5000.<ref>Josephine Powell, \"Tito Puente: When The Drums Are Dreaming\", Author House 2007.</ref>\n\nPresident [[John F. Kennedy]] attended a dinner given in his honor by the California Democratic Party at the Palladium on November 18, 1961.\n\nIn 1964, it was announced that none of the jazz bands scheduled were to be paid and a riot ensued after the show was cancelled.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\nThe Joe Loco Orchestra and show performed on the March 1965 Latin Holiday with singer/dancer Josephine \"Josie\" Powell.\n\nPop Expo '69, referred to as a \"teenage fair,\" was a youth-oriented event held from 28 March to 6 April 1969 at the Palladium, and included performances by [[The Jimi Hendrix Experience]] and the [[MC5]].\n\nIn 1973 Stevie Wonder performed with [[Taj Mahal (musician)|Taj Mahal]] in what was advertised as an \"Afrocentric concert\" to benefit African refugees.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\nBeginning in the 1980s and 90s, punk rock, [[Rap music|rap]] and [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] concerts started to be booked at the venue. Several white power disturbances resulted, eventually leading to the Palladium closing for eight weeks, starting in February 1993.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1994-12-14-ca-8811-story.html |title=Story |date=December 14, 1994 |website= www.latimes.com|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nSince 1985, the theater has been owned by Palladium Investors Ltd., a privately held group. Curfews were implemented in 1993 and a show by [[Marky Mark and the Funky Bunch]] was called off because of a brawl that occurred a few nights earlier, .<ref name=\"Light\"/> It was also used for Hollywood celebrity parties.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\n==Renovation and reopening==\nIn 2007, the owners agreed to a long-term lease to operate, manage and exclusively book the Hollywood Palladium with [[Live Nation]], a [[Los Angeles]]-based company.<ref name=\"billboardOct2008\"/>\n\nThe Palladium reopened with a Jay-Z concert on October 15, 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://filter-mag.com/index.php?id=14264&c=1 |title=Filter-Mag.com |publisher=Filter-mag.com |date= |accessdate=2008-11-29}}</ref> after a year-long, multimillion-dollar renovation by Live Nation. The renovation included an overhaul of the venue's interior and exterior, a new dance floor, expanded concessions, upgraded restrooms and improvements to the stage infrastructure. Jay-Z performed for nearly an hour-and-half, backed by an eight-piece band and [[DJ AM]], who played his first show after surviving a plane crash in South Carolina.<ref name=\"billboardOct2008\">{{Cite news|last=Peters |first=Mitchell |title=Jay-Z Christens New Hollywood Palladium |newspaper=Billboard Magazine |date=October 16, 2008 |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043761/jay-z-christens-new-hollywood-palladium |format=&ndash; <sup>[https://scholar.google.co.uk/scholar?hl=en&lr=&q=author%3APeters+intitle%3AJay-Z+Christens+New+Hollywood+Palladium&as_publication=&as_ylo=2008&as_yhi=2008&btnG=Search Scholar search]</sup> |postscript= |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131119080215/http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/1043761/jay-z-christens-new-hollywood-palladium |archivedate=November 19, 2013 |df= }}</ref> The Hollywood Palladium was also used as the memorial service site for [[DJ AM]] on September 3, 2009.<ref>{{cite news | author=Adam Bryant | title=DJ AM Funeral and Burial to Be Held Wednesday | url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/DJ-AM-Funeral-1009412.aspx | work=TVGuide.com | date=2 September 2009 | accessdate=2009-09-04}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2008-2009 season, a yearlong table for four cost $30,000.<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n\n===Residential expansion===\nAn expansion of the Palladium property parking lot was approved by the Los Angeles City council on March 2016. The plan consists of two 28 story residential towers that surrounds the historic music venue. Each tower will stand 350 feet tall and create 731 condominiums, 24,000 sq ft store front retail space and a below grade parking garage. The Towers were designed by [[Stanley Saitowits]] of [[Natoma Architects]] for developer Crescent Heights. The \"L\" shaped design resembles and echoes the [[Streamline Moderne]] - art deco design of the Palladium.\n\nThe local [[AIDS Healthcare Foundation]] (AHF) filed a lawsuit in 2016 citing over development and improper approval process. One of many local lawsuits filed by AHF president Michael Weinstein.<ref>{{cite web|author=July 13, 2018, 10:00AMSteven Sharp Comments |url=https://urbanize.la/post/hollywoods-palladium-development-score-legal-victory |title=Hollywood's Palladium Development Score a Legal Victory |publisher=Urbanize LA |date=2018-07-13 |accessdate=2020-01-20}}</ref> In August 2018, the district court ruled all steps were taken during [[California Environmental Quality Act|EIR/DEIR]]. The AHF filed a appeal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://urbanize.la/post/la-city-council-approves-palladium-residences|title=L.A. City Council Approves Palladium Residences|date=23 March 2016|publisher=|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref> The AHF lost the appeal in November 2019 and Crescent Heights plans to proceed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://urbanize.la/tags/hollywood-palladium |title=Hollywood Palladium News |publisher=Urbanize.la |date= |accessdate=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe Hollywood Palladium has been featured in many movies and TV shows over the years:\n*''[[The Day of the Locust]]'' (1975).<ref>Lawson, Kristan, & Rufus, Anneli (2000). ''California Babylon'', p. 35.  New York:  St. Martin's Press.</ref>\n*''[[Skatetown, U.S.A.]]'' (1979).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0079912/|title=Skatetown, U.S.A.|date=1 October 1979|publisher=|accessdate=27 June 2018|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/57090|title=AFI-Catalog|website=catalog.afi.com|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref>\n*The final concert scene in ''[[The Blues Brothers (film)|The Blues Brothers]]'' depicted as \"Palace Hotel Ballroom\". The exterior was actually the [[South Shore Cultural Center|South Shore Country Club]] in [[Chicago]]. (1980).<ref name=\"Light\"/>\n*Richard Pryor performed two dates in December 1981 and was filmed for the theatrical release ''[[Richard Pryor: Live on the Sunset Strip]]'' in March 1982.      \n*[[Keith Richards]] released a CD and DVD of his solo concert ''[[Live at the Hollywood Palladium, December 15, 1988]]''.\n* The [[punk rock|punk]] band [[Bad Religion]] recorded ''[[Live at the Palladium (Bad Religion DVD)|Live at the Palladium]]'' in 2006, a collection from their two days of performances.\n* [[Thrash Metal]] band [[Megadeth]] filmed a live DVD based on the 20th anniversary of their album ''[[Rust in Peace]]'' at The Palladium.\n* [[Luna Sea]] performed their first American concert at the Palladium on December 4, 2010. It was recorded in [[3D film|3D]] and released as both a live album and [[concert film]], ''[[Luna Sea 3D in Los Angeles]]''.<ref name=\"Luna Sea\">{{cite web| title= LUNA SEA announces the release date for their 3D live movie| work=Tokyo Hive| date= 2011-04-30| url=http://www.tokyohive.com/2011/04/luna-sea-announces-the-release-date-for-their-3d-live-movie/| accessdate = 2011-06-11}}</ref>\n*In 2016 Dave Chappelle filmed his Netflix special at Palladium.\n* The exterior appears in the final episode of Adam-12.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Architecture|Greater Los Angeles|National Register of Historic Places|Theatre}}\n*[[List of music venues in Los Angeles]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Los Angeles]]\n*[[Theater in California]]\n*[[House Of Blues]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n\n{{Grammy Award venues}}\n{{Live Nation}}\n{{National Register of Historic Places in California}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Hollywood]]\n[[Category:Music venues in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Concert halls in California]]\n[[Category:Hollywood history and culture]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sunset Boulevard (Los Angeles)]]\n[[Category:1940 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Streamline Moderne architecture in California]]\n[[Category:Theatres on the National Register of Historic Places in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award venues]]\n[[Category:Theatres completed in 1940]]\n", "name_user": "Albany NY", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn popular 